Fibrocartilage has a significant proportion of collagen type I fibres with little ground substance; densely-woven collagen type I and collagen type II fibres. The high proportion of collagen type I fibres in a cartilage-type ground substance creates a tissue that resists both compressive forces & tensile forces. It is intermediate in strength between hyaline cartilage and dense regular CT.  
Chondrocytes arrange in rows between bundles of collagen fibres. There is no perichondrium; the collagen type I fibres of fibrocartilage provide attachment to adjacent tissues. 
Fibrocartilage forms the annulus fibrosis of intervertebral disks and pubic symphysis, intra-articular disks, and found at entheses, tendon &  ligament insertions (fig).
